{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011Ccs2bkGDs8uWVYfjjNnns","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Certificate rotation complete and verified:\n\n**What was done:**\n- Used the existing CA (`/tmp/certs/ca.key` + `ca.crt` in the `openssl-toolbox` pod, same CA already trusted cluster-wide) to issue a fresh `node` cert (same SAN list, reused `node.cnf`) and a fresh `client.root` cert, both valid 365 days.\n- Updated the `crdb-cluster-certs` Secret in place with the new `node.crt`/`node.key`/`client.root.crt`/`client.root.key`.\n- Discovered CockroachDB v24.1.0 does **not** hot-reload the node cert from an updated secret volume mount — after ~90s the gRPC listener was still serving the old (soon-to-expire) cert. Confirmed via `openssl s_client` against port 26257.\n- Performed a one-pod-at-a-time rolling restart (`crdb-cluster-0` → `-1` → `-2`, each waited to become Ready before touching the next) to force each node to pick up the new cert. This was safe here — unlike the earlier insecure→TLS migration — because all nodes still share the same trusted CA, so mixed old/new leaf certs during the rollout don't break mutual trust or quorum.\n\n**Verification results:**\n1. `SELECT 1` over `--certs-dir` succeeds.\n2. New node cert fingerprint: `B5:35:17:40:...` (rotated from the old `D6:A9:2F:DC:...`).\n3. Validity: `2026-07-09` → `2027-07-09` (exactly 365 days).\n4. All 3 nodes now serve the new cert on the wire (checked live via TLS handshake), and `cockroach node status` shows all 3 nodes live/available."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":97,"cache_read_input_tokens":102686,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":97},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f58ac0a5-fcb2